# AI Coding Rules & Guidelines (Generated by ts-analyzer)

This project utilizes strict guidelines to maintain code quality, type safety, and low cyclomatic complexity. Please follow these rules when generating or modifying code.

## 1. Project Stack & Architecture
- **Language**: TypeScript
- **File Extension Rules**: Prefer `.ts` (logic) and `.tsx` (components) for new files.

## 2. Type Safety Standards
> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Current Project Type Safety Score is 46/100**. We are actively working to raise this score. Do not introduce untyped patterns.

- **Explicit Type Annotations**: Avoid relying purely on implicit types for public exports, function parameters, and class members.
- **No 'any' Types**: Do NOT use the `any` keyword. Use specific types, interfaces, generics, or `unknown` if the type is truly dynamic.
- **Avoid Type Assertions**: Do not use type assertions (`as Type` or `<Type>`) or non-null assertions (`!`) to bypass type-checking. Solve type issues structurally.
- **Type Coverage Target**: Ensure all new files have at least **95%** type coverage (current average is **77.6%**).

## 3. Code Complexity & Structure
> [!WARNING]
> **Average Function Cyclomatic Complexity is high (13.3)**. Focus on simplifying conditionals and splitting logic.

- **Keep Functions Small**: Keep functions focused on a single responsibility. Prefer functions under **15** lines of code (current average is **84.3** lines).
- **Nesting Limit**: Do not nest logic blocks (if, for, while, switch) deeper than **3** levels. (Callback Hell/deep nesting has been flagged in this codebase; avoid adding to it).
- **Limit Function Parameters**: Keep parameter lists to a maximum of **4** variables. For more parameters, pass an options object or interface.
- **God Files / Size Limit**: Avoid large files. Split code into modules smaller than **500** lines. (Currently there are 2 file(s) exceeding 500 lines).

## 4. Best Practices & Quality Checks
- **Anti-Patterns to Avoid**:
  - Magic Numbers: Define constants with descriptive names instead of inline raw values.
  - Nested Ternaries: Use readable if-else blocks or switch statements instead of complex inline ternaries.
  - Re-assigning parameters: Do not modify incoming arguments directly; treat them as immutable.
- **Validation**: Run `ts-analyzer` locally to verify your code doesn't decrease the overall Type Safety or Complexity metrics.
